### Part 5: Server — setPlayerName method (server/game.js)

Add to the Game class (after `handleInput` method):
```js
setPlayerName(playerId, name) {
  const player = this.players.get(playerId);
  if (!player) return;

  if (typeof name !== 'string') {
    player.name = `Player ${playerId}`;
    return;
  }

  const trimmed = name.trim().slice(0, 16);
  player.name = trimmed.length > 0 ? trimmed : `Player ${playerId}`;
}
```

The `name` field is already broadcast in `getState()` (line 578: `name: p.name`) — no changes needed there.

### Part 6: Tests (test/game.test.js)

Add after the existing "Shoot cooldown prevents rapid fire" test:
```js
test('setPlayerName validates and sets nickname', () => {
  const game = new Game();
  const mockWs = { readyState: 1, send: () => {} };
  const id = game.addPlayer(mockWs);

  // Default name
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === `Player ${id}`, 'default name is Player N');

  // Valid name
  game.setPlayerName(id, 'TestUser');
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === 'TestUser', 'valid name accepted');

  // Whitespace trimmed
  game.setPlayerName(id, '  Padded  ');
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === 'Padded', 'whitespace trimmed');

  // Max 16 chars
  game.setPlayerName(id, 'ThisNameIsWayTooLongForLimit');
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === 'ThisNameIsWayToo', 'truncated to 16 chars');

  // Empty string falls back
  game.setPlayerName(id, '');
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === `Player ${id}`, 'empty falls back to Player N');

  // Whitespace-only falls back
  game.setPlayerName(id, '   ');
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === `Player ${id}`, 'whitespace-only falls back');

  // Non-string falls back
  game.setPlayerName(id, 12345);
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === `Player ${id}`, 'non-string falls back');

  // Null falls back
  game.setPlayerName(id, null);
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === `Player ${id}`, 'null falls back');

  // Invalid player ID does nothing
  game.setPlayerName(9999, 'Ghost');
  assert(game.players.get(id).name === `Player ${id}`, 'invalid id is no-op');
});

test('Custom nickname appears in game state', () => {
  const game = new Game();
  const mockWs = { readyState: 1, send: () => {} };
  const id = game.addPlayer(mockWs);
  game.setPlayerName(id, 'CustomName');
  const state = game.getState(id);
  const playerState = state.players.find(p => p.id === id);
  assert(playerState.name === 'CustomName', 'custom name in serialized state');
});
```

## Gotchas

- The `nicknameInput` variable must be declared BEFORE the keydown/keyup listeners reference it via `document.activeElement` check. Since the input is in the HTML, `document.getElementById` will work at script load time.
- Don't use `e.stopPropagation()` for the nickname input — instead use the `document.activeElement` guard in the game's key handlers. This is cleaner and doesn't interfere with normal input behavior.
- The nickname input should NOT have `autofocus` — it would capture WASD on page load.
- When checking `document.activeElement`, compare against the actual element, not a string.
- The `setPlayerName` method should handle edge cases: player might have disconnected between message send and processing, name might not be a string.
- The `trim()` must happen BEFORE `slice(0, 16)` is wrong — actually `trim()` should happen first, then `slice`. Wait — the order matters: trim first removes surrounding whitespace, then slice truncates. If you slice first, you might keep trailing whitespace. So: `name.trim().slice(0, 16)` is correct.
- Run `npm test` after changes to verify all 865+ existing tests still pass plus new ones.
